@node Introduction "Introduction"

I. INTRODUCTION

    Welcome back to yet another goofy Arexx script!  Once I got the
Personal Animation Recorder, I tore into making this script.  I had a
functional [although not pretty] script inside a few hours.  A week
or so later, the script was polished and ready to be released.

    Although what this script does will most likely only be used by
professionals, compared to the Video Panel Machine, it kind of pales
in comparison when you take into consideration the complexity and
number of features. Because of this I made The Field Machine a freebie.
However, if you could drop me a line with registration information,
that would be great.

SEE: @{"Registration" link Registration}

@endnode

@node Installation "Installation

II. INSTALLATION

    The following steps must be taken to properly install the Field
Machine.

1. You MUST be using OpalPaint version 2.3 or higher.

2. If you haven't already, Create a "Rexx" [no quotes] drawer inside
your "OpalPaint:" directory.  "OpalPaint:" Should already be assigned
to the drawer that holds your OpalPaint program.

3. Copy the following files into your "OpalPaint:Rexx" drawer:

        FieldMachine.oprx
        FieldMachine-Quick.oprx
        FieldMachineDefault.TXT

4. Inside your "Images24:" directory, create a drawer called
"Stencils" [again, no quotes in the drawer name].  Copy the following
file into your "Images24:Stencils" directory.

        FieldMachine.Sten

5. In OpalPaint v2.3 or higher, Hit Amiga-a and you will be greeted
by the Arexx Requestor.  Click inside one of the text fields, and
enter "FieldMachine.oprx" in one and "FieldMachine-Quick.oprx" in
another.

    The FieldMachine is now installed in your OpalPaint system.  Be
sure to read the rest of the documentation to understand how to
operate the FieldMachine scripts.

@endnode

@node WhatItDoes "What the Field Machine does"

III. WHAT THE FIELD MACHINE DOES

    So what is the Field Machine for anyhow?  Well, if you do not
have access to playing back your 24-bit animations in video
resolution at true 30 frames per second [25 in PAL], you do not have
a huge need for the Field Machine.  On the other hand, if you have
a Personal Animation Recorder or the ability to single-frame record
your animations to videotape, you do have a need for the Field
Machine.

    Each frame of video is made up of two fields.  Every odd scanline
of a frame belongs to the first field, and every even scanline
makes up the second field.  When a video frame is displayed, it is
shoved out to the screen a field at a time.  What the Field Machine
does is take two images or "fields" and combines them into a full
video frame.  When these "field rendered" frames are played in
succession, 30 a second, your animated motion as actually twice as
smooth.  60 images [read: fields] per second [50 in PAL].  The result
is a very smooth animation that is more professional looking.

    NOTE: The Field Machine only EMULATES field rendering.  It is not
TRUE field rendering.  The only way to get TRUE field rendering is
with a 3D system designed to do so.  Despite this fack, the output of
the Field Machine is very, very good.

    Another drawback of the script is the limited resolution of the
OpalVision display.  True NTSC Video is roughly 750 x 482 but this
script only creates frames at about 736 x 470 for NTSC.  It's not
at all noticable on a regular television set, but professionals who
KNOW video may sniff out this limitation at first glance of their
overscan/underscan monitor.  It *IS* possible for me to have this
script do full 750 x 482, but because of the round-about way it takes
to do this would slow down the script considerably.  If the extra
resolution is important to you, let me know in your Registration
[maybe accompanied by a donation] and I'll make a version that does
full video frames.

@endnode

@node HowToUseIt "How to Use the Field Machine"

IV. HOW TO USE THE FIELD MACHINE

    There are two versions of the Field Machine.  FieldMachine.oprx
and FieldMachine-Quick.oprx.  Let's deal with the first version.

    Before using the Field Machine script, you will need an
animation.  Or at least, an program ready to crank out an animation
such as a 3D animation system.

    Your animation frames MUST be inside a drawer of some sort.  They
may not exists in the root directory of a disk or device.  The Field
Machine will not be able to find your frames unless they are inside a
directory.  99.9 times out of a hundred, your frames will be inside a
drawer.

    Your animation should be created to be played out at 60 images
per second [50 in PAL].  Or, twice as slow as normal 30 [25 in PAL]
frames per second video.

    Your animation frames should be in the name format of pic.0001,
pic.0002, pic.0003, etc...  The frames of your animation must not
start with a number lower than pic.0001.  You can start your
animation at any number higher than pic.0001.  Of course, the frame
number format limits your animation from exceeding pic.9999.

    If your animation frames, perhaps created by a 3D program, are
not in the format of pic.0001, etc., there is a solution.  I have
created a script called FrameNamer.  FrameNamer easily converts
animation file name formats from any format to any format.  As long
as there is some sort of number system in your frame names, FrameName
can convert it quickly and easily.  Look for FNamer.LHA on finer BBS
systems everywhere.

    If you are using a 3D animation system to create your animation
frames, you do NOT have to wait for it to render all your frames
before running the Field Machine.  If the Field Machine cannot
find the next frame, it will wait until the frame is rendered.  The
Field Machine will check every minute to see if the frame is
completed.  WARNING!  If you accidentally tell the Field Machine to
look for your animation frames in the wrong directory, the Field
Machine will wait and wait and wait and get nothing accomplished.
Another note here, your 3D program of choice will need it save it's
images in the pic.0001 format for the Field Machine to detect them.

    The first requestor you will see when running the Field Machine
is a confirmation requestor.  This is basically a title requestor so
you can make sure that you didn't accidentally launch the wrong
script.  Click on QUIT to abort the script, or click on NTSC or PAL,
depending on where you live.  If you live in the United States,
choose NTSC.  If you live outside the United States, odds are you
will want to choose PAL [You lucky people, you, I'm a yank and there-
fore must live with NTSC].

    The next requestor asks you what the pathname is for your
animation frames.  Enter in the PATHNAME only.  Not any of your
filenames.  You can choose to use a file requestor if it makes things
easier.

    The next thing that pops up is the requestor for choosing the
FIRST and LAST frame numbers of your animation.  Enter in normal
numbers only. 1,35, etc.. Not things like "pic.0001" or "0026."

    The FIRST frame number must be an ODD number.  The LAST frame
number must be an EVEN number.  The reason for this is that it takes
2 fields to make a frame.  Your images are handled in pairs.  First
an ODD number frame, then the next frame, which of course would be
EVEN.  Choosing 1 for the FIRST field image and 2 for the SECOND
field image will result in 1 frame.  Makes sense, no?

    The last requestor is fairly complicated.  Here you choose which
method to use for merging your fields into frames.

    The first section, "Choose destination resolution of frames"
has a CROP OR SCALE gadget, and a RESOLUTION gadget.

    If you render your images larger than you ultimately need them,
the Field Machine can scale them down to the requested size and
this will improve your animation frames' anti-aliasing.  This is
especially true for images that are at least twice the size they
need to be.  If you intend to do this, use the "Scale to" option
of the first gadget.
    If your 3D program cannot create images at a resolution of
736x476, but it can create them at a resolution of 768x482 or
something similar, use the "Crop to" setting for the first
gadget and choose the 736x476 value for the resolution gadget.  The
result will be your field images placed directly in the center of
the 736x476 frame, with the extra resolution lost.  No big deal for
a difference of 32x6 pixels.
    The resolution gadget is to choose the resolution of the
DESTINATION "field rendered" images.  This does not have to be
the resolution of your SOURCE field images.

    The next section of the requestor gives you two options.
"Retain full height of field" and "Compress fields to half height."

    Retaining the full height of your field images means that when
the two field images are merged, every-other scanline in your field
image is lost.

    Compressing fields to half height is going to squash your field
images to half their size before merging.  This way, every two
scanlines are blended into one.  This gives you a bit more definition
but if your subject (or background) is standing still it will appear
to have half of the horizontal resolution.

    One advantage to this feature is that in your 3D system you can
render your field images with half the horizontal resolution in the
first place.  This means roughly half the rendering time.  If your
destination "field rendered" animation is to have 476 horizontal
resolution, render your frames with a horizontal resolution of 238.
Pretty simple, and a tremendous time saver.

    Retaining the full height of your field images is really the best
way to go for quality.  And if you are using a handy-dandy OpalPaint
script to generate your animation, might as well use the full height
option.  The time difference for creating frames in OpalPaint to
generating frames in a 3D animation system *CAN* be tremendous.

    The last section of the requestor simply asks you if you want to
delete your original field images once a frame is successfully
merged.  Most times you will choose the use this option.  It's a
tremendous storage saver.  Unless you need your original field images
for another project, place a check in the box.

    One more requestor pops up to tell you "Here we go."  From this
point on, OpalPaint takes over and you are free to do other things,
such as freeing the world from Zylaxxian invasion at your local
arcade.

    You can use the QUICK version of the Field Machine IF AND ONLY IF
your SOURCE field images are EXACTLY the same as your DESTINATION
frame resolution.  Your options are:

NTSC:
736x476
640x400
368x236
320x200
160x100

PAL:
736x576
640x512
368x286
320x256
160x128

    The fields will be merged in the format of "Retain full height"
and of course will loose every-other scanline in the process.

    The quick version of of course, quicker.  This reason is no
image scaling is required, and the images can be loaded as pictures
instead of brushes.  The normal version MUST load it's images as
brushes because some scale methods require SMOOTH method and others
require BLOCKY method.


@endnode

